The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Two passengers were killed and one was injured in two mishaps 

 on the tracks on the northern fringes of the city on Sunday 

 morning. Brahma Nanda, 60, was hit by a Sealdah-bound train 

 at Khardah station around 8.30 am. He was rushed to a local 

 hospital, where he was pronounced dead. 

 Prasenjit Biswas, 18, a resident of Pairadanga, in Nadia, 

 died after falling off a local train at Belghoria station. 

 Friend Biltu Sarkar suffered injuries while trying to save 

 Prasenjit. Biltu was taken to NRS Medical College and Hospital, 

 from where he was released after first-aid. An investigation 

 has been ordered. 

 A woman in her 70s died after being knocked down by a private bus on route 18C at the crossing of Rashbehari Avenue and Gariahat Road on Sunday afternoon. Police said the woman was trying to cross the intersection. Local residents took the her to Ramakrishna Mission Seva Pratishthan, where doctors pronounced her dead. The driver of the bus managed to flee.

 Kavita Kamlia, 21, committed suicide by consuming poison at her Chetla home early on Sunday. Police said Kavita, unmarried, had conceived a few weeks ago. A hunt is on for the youth, a Lake Gardens resident, with whom Kavita was having an affair. No suicide note was found.

 A sleaze racket was busted in Baruipur, on the southern fringes of the city, on Saturday night following the arrest of 11 persons, including five girls. Police said those arrested, including a kingpin identified as Rekha, were from Tiljala, Sonarpur and other fringe areas. The other two kingpins are absconding.

 A website on Satyajit Ray will be inaugurated later this month by Satyajit Ray Society. The website will feature hundreds of photographs of Ray, including some rare ones, and also his write-ups. A special section will be devoted to Rays storyboard on Pandit Ravi Shankar.

 Around 200 students of Aryans School in Agarpara, on the northern fringes of the city, organised a seminar on detection of thalassaemia and its prevention. Mayoral council member (health), Calcutta Municipal Corporation, Subodh Dey attended the conference. The school authorities have also undertaken a programme to detect thalassaemia among students in the locality.

 Members of the Bakers Coordination Committee and Joint Action Committee have called an emergency meeting with the state government to ensure flour used in making bread is made available at the regulated price. The members claimed that prices of all ingredients required to make bread have shot up.

 State Bank of India has opened a Liability Central Process Centre in the city to centralise services to its clients. Customers will be able to open accounts quickly at branches of their choice and will immediately receive a kit containing a non-personalised ATM Card and a cheque book. A personalised ATM card will be supplied from the centre directly to the customer.

